\par\par \b \uc2  Expert urges abolishment of export  \highlight22\uc2 taxes \highlight\uc2  to boots revenue. \b0\par\par\uc2 579 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 August 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Eliminating the export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the only way to boost foreign exchange revenue from exports and allow businesses to optimally benefit from the sharp depreciation of the rupiah, an economist believes. \par \par \uc2  Djisman Simandjuntak of the Prasetya Mulya school of management said it would be the only feasible way because providing exporters with other incentives, like cheap export credit in the 1980s, was unrealistic given the government's limited \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "The best export \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be a combination of a tight macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the elimination of export restrictions, including export \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he said at a seminar last week. \par \par \uc2  Indonesian exporters have faced various \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  and nontariff export restrictions since 1993, including in the form of cartels and quotas designed to protect domestic industries. \par \par \uc2  Nontariff restrictions have been abandoned following an agreement with the International Monetary Fund (IMF), but export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on many commodities remains. \par \par \uc2  Although export \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on leather, cork, ores and waste aluminum have been abolished, those on major export contributors including logs, sawn timber, rattan and minerals have only been reduced to 30 percent. A reduction to 20 percent is expected by year's end. \par \par \uc2  Djisman said the sharp depreciation of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar failed in boosting export revenue because other currencies in the region were also devaluated. Indonesia's high inflation, which reached more than 60 percent during the first seven months of this year, ate up much of the gains made from the dollar appreciation, he added. \par \par \uc2  "If the inflation rate in 1998 moves near the 100 percent level, a large part of the benefit from the rupiah depreciation will be eroded," he said, stressing the importance of a tight macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to curb inflation. \par \par \uc2  He said total export revenues during the first four months of the year were relatively deficient given the 80 percent drop in the rupiah's value. \par \par \uc2  "The slow export growth may also be caused by the limited investment made in export industries since 1993." \par \par \uc2  He explained that the expansive monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  since 1993 and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure which made local-market orientation more profitable than exports had discouraged businesspeople from entering the export-oriented industry. \par \par \uc2  Although the previous regime of Soeharto embarked on various deregulatory measures during the 1990s, there was increasing discrimination in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  implementation. It allowed several investors to garner large windfall profits from monopolizing the local market, including the property sector, infrastructure, and import substitution industry. \par \par \uc2  Local exporters are also experiencing problems in importing raw materials due to the rejection of local letters of credit (L/C) by overseas banks in the wake of low confidence in domestic banks. However, the overseas credit line had started to return following the L/C guarantee by various foreign governments and the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  High \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  have also created cash-flow difficulties for many exporters. \par \par \uc2  About 21 local banks have been appointed by the government to solve the problem, but exporters said the scheme had yet to work. \par \par \uc2  The political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that followed the May 21 resignation of Soeharto has also deterred international buyers who fear local manufacturers will be unable to meet delivery deadlines. \par \par \uc2  The country's footwear association has forecast exports to decline by 25 percent this year from $1.9 billion last year, and the textile association projects export this year to decline by $1.5 billion from $7.3 billion in 1997. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du8v005h7\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
