\par\par \b \uc2  Political players need to negotiate. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Rizal Mallaranggeng \par \uc2 1,140 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 September 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The following article is based on a paper presented at a discussion on finding a "new vision" in the post-Soeharto era held by the Center for Strategic and International Studies on Aug. 25. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The reform process is entering a critical period in which it could result in either a form of anarchy or democracy. \par \par \uc2  Should the country fail to advance the reform process effectively, we will find ourselves facing a "consolidated anarchy" in our political institutions. Complications within the political system and institutions would hamper institutional development. \par \par \uc2  In this case, reforms would only take place unsystematically, without a clear blueprint. Worse still, such changes would be made simultaneously with other actions contrary to the logic of the reform itself. \par \par \uc2  Therefore, consolidated anarchy would result in a political situation marked by a high degree of political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , cynicism, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  turmoil and continuing ethno-religious suspicions. \par \par \uc2  A return to authoritarian rule - with militaristic and despotic characteristics - cannot be ruled out if such a condition persists for a few years. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, if the country can smoothly pass this critical period, we could be heading for a form of democracy. \par \par \uc2  If a democratic system and institutions can be developed, the reform process could end in the creation of what is termed as a "consolidated democracy". \par \par \uc2  Such a result would not eliminate basic conflicts but at least they would be institutionalized. Each political camp involved would have to adhere to the rules of the same political game. \par \par \uc2  Indonesians would also be able to return to a "normal" life in the sense that the political stage would be filled by politicians, activists and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  figures instead of marching protesters. \par \par \uc2  Should we be able to achieve a consolidated democracy, Indonesia could become a model of democracy for other developing nations through good examples of how ethnic and religious conflicts can be settled peacefully. \par \par \uc2  The question is, how do we get there? \par \par \uc2  Is such a system obtainable peacefully and without sacrificing the systematic and rational steps needed to solve the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis? \par \par \uc2  Unfortunately, nobody knows. Social science experts cannot really see into the future with any certainty. As Max Weber said, only demagogues are able to make predictions, not social scientists. \par \par \uc2  But to achieve a working democratic system, some preconditions are in order. First, there needs to be a desire and the ability to negotiate, while secondly, there needs to be a clear and realistic choice of priorities in the country's political agenda. \par \par \uc2  Why are these important? In order to answer this question, we must first consider something that has never been seriously discussed by the media: the nature of the political transition taking place toward the fall of the New Order regime and its aftermath. \par \par \uc2  The current political situation can be characterized as having a negative balance of forces among various groups, from reformists as well as from current power holders. \par \par \uc2  Since Soeharto's fall, no single group has really possessed sufficient power to win absolutely. The reformists and the middle class can point to having moral strength and truth in their arguments, but they are divided, unorganized and are relatively small in number. \par \par \uc2  If the reformists did not suffer from these weaknesses, the political situation would be much different from the one we face now. \par \par \uc2  On the other hand, elements that made up the New Order regime can count on organization and money, though they too are divided and, most importantly, are severely demoralized. \par \par \uc2  The fact that no one group can take absolute control of the political arena has resulted in a situation in which all sides, both the reformists and the elements supporting the status quo, can only point to partial wins over the past three months. \par \par \uc2  The reformists scored a partial victory when Soeharto stepped down, but other aspects of their demands seem to have been forgotten. \par \par \uc2  The resulting stalemate has resulted in a political transition that can be called a reforma pactada, a reform that must be negotiated, like the one in Spain in the 1970s. \par \par \uc2  Since each camp cannot win the political fight at this point, both reformists and the power holders should realize that a process of negotiations needs to take place to further the reform process to a stage in which institutional changes can be made. \par \par \uc2  Hence the will and the capacity to negotiate at this moment are absolute requirements to push our political transition process another step farther. \par \par \uc2  We must understand that consolidated democracy is a political objective. In a reforma pactada situation, this objective can only be attained through negotiations. \par \par \uc2  It may look simple, but it is this aspect that gives cause for great worry. For too long, we have not been trained to compromise. All sides, including reformists, often demand absolute terms - thus narrowing the room for compromise. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, the possibility for negotiations is only open if a kind of trust exists among the contesting sides. \par \par \uc2  Regrettably, what is flourishing now is chronic mistrust, a mistrust against anybody, including among the reformists themselves. \par \par \uc2  Recognizing reform priorities or creating a simple and realistic agenda is also a necessary precondition to attaining a consolidated democracy. \par \par \uc2  In this case, the reformists "outside the system", as well as the sympathizers of reform ideas "inside the system", must be able to see clearly that the most important priority in this transitional period is the creation of a clean and fair general election which could result in a legitimate legislature. \par \par \uc2  Only a legislature with a recognized \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  mandate can endeavor to create the institutionalization needed to form a democracy. In other words, a clean election is the bridge to the next phase of reform. \par \par \uc2  Like the aspect of negotiation, the choice of priorities looks simple and insignificant. But if we read the newspapers and follow television news and analyses, we see that a sense of priority is not clear. \par \par \uc2  Before May 21, the priorities of the reformists were clear: take out Soeharto. Now, is there anybody who can give a simple explanation as to what is the most important thing to do? \par \par \uc2  We read, hear and see too many things to be fought for or to be done simultaneously. We are inundated by various reform agendas. This is understandable, but the consequence is that the reform process loses its focus. \par \par \uc2  By choosing a clean election as the main priority in the reform agenda, we may be able to forget for the moment a number of things that may be interesting but not urgent if seen from a wider perspective. \par \par \uc2  It is we who must choose. Indeed, we should not forget that politics is basically an art to determine a course given a limited number of choices. \par \par \uc2  Rizal Malaranggeng is a PhD candidate in political science at Ohio State University in the United States. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \