\par\par \b \uc2  Further unrest disrupts local financial market. \b0\par\par\uc2 567 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 September 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Continuing unrest in the country sent the local financial market into a tailspin on Monday, with the rupiah hitting 11,950 against the U.S. dollar and the stock market falling to another five-year low. \par \par \uc2  Currency dealers and stockbrokers said the news reports of looting and riots in Medan, North Sumatra, dragged down market sentiment on the rupiah and local stocks. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said the rupiah opened at 11,750, lower than Friday's close of 11,650. \par \par \uc2  However, dollar sales by state banks saved the currency from falling further and even boosted it to 11,550 by the close of trading. \par \par \uc2  "Without such intervention, the rupiah for sure would have tottered because of all of the unrest," a chief dealer with a local private bank said. \par \par \uc2  It was reported that shops were looted and buildings damaged when thousands of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transport workers rallied in Medan on Monday in the latest protest against escalating prices. \par \par \uc2  The workers gathered at the provincial governor's office shouting slogans and demanding the government lower prices of spare parts and basic commodities. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said that Indonesia's ravaged financial market had not recovered yet as the government had not fully introduced clear-cut measures to pull the country out of its dire \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. \par \par \uc2  "The rupiah might sink to between 12,000 and 12,500 in the days ahead," a dealer with another local private bank said, pointing out that unresolved political and social \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  at home would pose a major problem for the shattered rupiah. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) index also fell, with the JSX Composite Price Index closing 3.44 points lower to 320.59. \par \par \uc2  Trading turnover totaled 182.78 million shares valued at Rp 229.96 billion. \par \par \uc2  Stock brokers said the absence of fresh leads in the local market combined with news reports of fresh riots and looting in Medan was responsible for market staying in the doldrums. \par \par \uc2  "Though other regional markets rose, our market was down. Market fears that riots in Medan could sear tensions in other cities have scared investors away," the head of research of BNI Securities, Adrian Lesmana, said. \par \par \uc2  Stock prices increased slightly in the morning on renewed buying orders by short-term investors. \par \par \uc2  But after the riots broke out in Medan, selling ruled the market in the afternoon, sending the price index down. \par \par \uc2  In time of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , no long-term investors would enter the market and only short-term investors were prepared to trade in local stocks. \par \par \uc2  "There are no long-term investors now. Most existing investors just buy stocks in the morning and take profits in the afternoon," Adrian said. \par \par \uc2  Stock analysts said the local market would continue to be depressed until the government introduced much-needed efforts to improve the country's wrecked \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Most blue chips stocks fell Monday, with state-owned telecommunication firm PT Telkom falling Rp 25 to Rp 2,000 on 2.84 million shares. \par \par \uc2  State-owned tin miner PT Tambang Timah slid Rp 475 to Rp 4,100 on 127,500 shares changing hands, state cement maker PT Semen Gresik was down Rp 150 to Rp 8,250 on 3,44 million shares, and state general mining firm PT Aneka Tambang fell Rp 25 to Rp 1,375 on 3,04 million shares. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924du9f005xg\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  RI rules out forex controls. \b0\par\par\uc2 716 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 September 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  The government has again made clear that Indonesia will continue to apply the free forex system and has no plan to peg the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Syahril Sabirin said here yesterday that the management of a monetary system takes into account two aspects, namely the forex system and exchange rate. \par \par \uc2  "As far as the forex system is concerned, Indonesia will not budge and will continue to apply the free forex system. Concerning the exchange rate, we will adhere to the free floating system." \par \par \uc2  Syahril, in comments to Malaysia's decision to apply forex control, said that "we are studying the case, but that is not akin to forex control." \par \par \uc2  IMF diector Hubert Neiss said in Seoul that short-term currency controls in Asia could stem the contagion effect. \par \par \uc2  He does not recommend the system for Indonesia, but admitted that the IMF is thoroughly studying what Malaysia has done. \par \par \uc2  When pointed out that applying the currency band contains seeds of risks that foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be used to intervene, Syahril said "that depends on whether we will apply tightly the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 's liquidity or its monetary system." \par \par \uc2  On protests from members of the real sector over high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said that now would not be the right time to lower them as such a move would only weaken the rupiah against the dollar. \par \par \uc2  Syahril added that BI is not intervening "in the conventional sense of the term." \par \par \uc2  Supply of the dollar to the market, he said, is done in conformation with what the government requires from foreign loans. \par \par \uc2  "If the government needs US$100 million, it would be exchanged in the market but on a piecemeal basis." \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, BI director Subarjo Joyosumarto said that easing liquidity restrictions will be done through the market mechanism. \par \par \uc2  "\b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are basically determined by the market. By way of Sertifikat \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (SBI) auctions, \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are lowered and maintained in stages," he said here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Subarjo added that BI will endeavor not to raise the rates, and that "if the market determines that rates are low, so be it." \par \par \uc2  "So there are no BI activities to raise again SBI rates. The way to lower the rates is to make available money to the market." \par \par \uc2  "The current level of money in circulation allows it to be increased so that the rates could fall. So far BI has never lowered the rates. It is done by the market. Lower SBI rates are reflected by the average rates of the weekly SBI auctions." \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  data show that the average rate of SBI last week (9 September) is 69.9%, a drop from that of the week before of 70.59%. \par \par \uc2  One banker who recently took part in a closed meeting with BI said that speculations abound the government is de-internationalizing rupiah traded overseas. \par \par \uc2  "The government is also seeking ways to repatriate export-derived funds. \par \par \uc2  On the possibility of currency controls in Indonesia, senior economist M. Sadli said that such a move could be possible once the rupiah has stabilized. \par \par \uc2  He supported the IMF's rejection of applying capital controls here. \par \par \uc2  "But in Indonesia's case, the application must conform to prevailing conditions. It's not feasible to do it now. But maybe in one year's time, when everything has returned to calm," Sadli told Bisnis here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  He said that IMF's revised stance on capital control means that it has doubts on its "orthodox methods." \par \par \uc2  Econit economists Rizal Ramli and Arif Arryman also agreed that IMF seems to have begun to rethink its approach to Indonesia \par \par \uc2  This, he added, showed that the IMF has failed to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Businessman Peter F. Gontha - he once advocated currency controls through the CBS [currency board system] - said that it was already too late for Indonesia to apply capital controls. \par \par \uc2  "In any case, applying controls is a dilemma for Indonesia." \par \par \uc2  "If it is not applied, investors face \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while non-application aslo means the absence of new investors," he said. \par \par \uc2  He added that many countries implement currency controls, namely South Korea, Taiwan, the Philippines, Singapore and now Malaysia. \par \par \uc2  "The difference is that Indonesia has come under pressure from foreigners not to impose capital controls," said Gontha. (ab/m2/hl/ass). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922du9g000pp\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
