\par\par \b \uc2  Political moves key to  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  cure. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Sofyan Wanandi. \par \uc2 1,518 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 October 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles based on a paper presented at the "Indonesia Update 1998" Conference in Melbourne from Sept. 25 to Sept 26, 1998. \par \par \uc2  MELBOURNE: It is unfortunate that anti-Chinese issues, and in fact stronger anti-Chinese feelings, are being aired at a time when Indonesia is entering a new era, the era of reformation, an era of greater respect for human rights and democratic ideals. Perhaps this is a result of the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the past government not to discuss these issues in the open. \par \par \uc2  Moreover, there indeed was a set back under the Soeharto regime in terms of nation building in general and the integration of the Chinese-Indonesian into society. It became more difficult for Chinese-Indonesians to enter the civil service and many other professions which led to their concentration in business activities. \par \par \uc2  In Soeharto's view they perform best in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, therefore they should concentrate in that field. Having them out of politics and other non-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  professions increased the political and social vulnerability of the group. \par \par \uc2  This allows them to be used as an instrument for the mobilization of financial resources for the regime in exchange for political "protection". This was Soeharto's strategy, and indeed it was also accepted by the majority of the Chinese-Indonesians, either because they had no alternative or because they do benefit materially from this strategy. \par \par \uc2  It is totally wrong, however, to believe that Chinese-Indonesian business dominates the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It is unbelievable that even educated persons uncritically accept the suggestion (the myth) that Chinese-Indonesians control 70 percent of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Perhaps it makes more sense if 70 percent of activities by the national private sector are undertaken by Chinese-Indonesian business. But the national private sector is at best perhaps 60 percent of the total private sector with the remainder consisting of foreign enterprises, multinationals and joint ventures. \par \par \uc2  The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity of the total private sector is perhaps 60 percent of total \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity with the remainder under the control of the state. Thus, at the most, Chinese-Indonesian businesses constitute 25 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 's activity, and not 70 percent as widely reported in the popular media. \par \par \uc2  Involvement in 25 percent of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity of the country does not mean control of 25 percent of the nation's assets. It is probably less since a large proportion of Chinese-Indonesian businesses are in such sectors as trading, which do not involve large investments. Yet, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  involvement of the "group" is relatively large in view of the fact that it constitutes only about 3 percent of the population. \par \par \uc2  Should asset redistribution be on the nation's agenda? This depends on what asset redistribution means and how it will be achieved. A more equitable distribution of the fruits of development should definitely be the objective of national development. This can be achieved through the introduction of policies to strengthen the weak and to empower the underprivileged. \par \par \uc2  There is a role for the government here. It can redistribute resources through the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  with the use of progressive \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  and by redirecting the resources to infrastructure development that help open up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  opportunities for the population at large, education and health, and many other training programs. Poor governance has been the main reason this has not happened, despite the fact that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has grown by an average of 7 percent per annum over the past three decades. \par \par \uc2  There is much talk about an affirmative action type of intervention by the government, similar to Malaysia's already abandoned NEP (New \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ). This is one possible way to redistribute assets. However, it is so often overlooked in Indonesia that to institute such a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  requires an explicit agreement between the groups concerned. \par \par \uc2  In Malaysia it was negotiated amongst the various groups and resulted in a genuine national consensus. In Indonesia, such a negotiation cannot even be held because there is no "group" representing the Chinese-Indonesians. A second requirement for this scheme to work is that it should be undertaken in a transparent manner. In an environment of such poor practices of governance as in Indonesia it is doubtful that such a requirement can be fulfilled. \par \par \uc2  Unless this issue of the role and place of the Chinese-Indonesian in society and in business is settled satisfactorily, desirably and once and for all, it is difficult to expect that confidence will return. The trauma of the May 1998 riots is very deep. Rioting that results in the damaged property of Chinese-Indonesians is not a new thing and to some extent has been regarded as some kind of social cost. \par \par \uc2  Each time, they will recover and start again. This time the situation is different. Never before have they felt so totally hopeless and unprotected. There is a widespread feeling that the government has allowed this to happen, and even that some sections of the government were behind the campaigns targeting Chinese-Indonesians. \par \par \uc2  What was not helpful was the defensive attitude on the part of the Habibie government. This transition government cannot be blamed and was not blamed for the riots. President Habibie expressed some sympathy by visiting Jakarta's "Chinatown", Glodok. Yet, it took him time to clearly condemn the action. This was the minimum that was required to heal the deep wounds. Human rights activities have demanded far more, namely for the government to find those responsible for the action and to punish them. \par \par \uc2  It appears that this demand has become necessary to restore confidence, in view of the fact that looting has become so widespread. The targets are no longer solely the Chinese-Indonesians. It is something much more serious. Not a single day goes by without reports of looting in various parts of the country. The business community is, of course, very sensitive to this kind of development. With the continued worsening of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation, such looting is likely to get worse. This will cause a further deterioration of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The business community in general sees gloom and doom on the horizon. \par \par \uc2  Finally, the continued \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the political sphere is a major factor influencing the outlook for business. The business community wants to see a quick political settlement. This is not possible. The best to hope for is a smooth implementation of the political agenda and timetable as proposed by the government, beginning with a special session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) in November 1998 to set the framework for the general elections in May 1999 to be followed by a general session of the MPR at the end of 1999. \par \par \uc2  The following 15 months will be extremely important. Yet, there is great anxiety that the country is running out of time. If more and more people are hungry and angry, there can be no guarantee that the process will be smooth. \par \par \uc2  The political situation today is as precarious as the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation and each influences the other. But the political side must make the first move. That is why there is something called "political will". Both the government and the more established groups in society must have the political will to move the process forward in a manner that creates confidence in the society at large. \par \par \uc2  Habibie on his part must reiterate his genuine resolve not to be re-elected in December 1999. Political figures like Amien Rais, Megawati and Gus Dur must come together to hammer out a new national consensus. The tragedy of Indonesia today is that these political figures are not in the MPR. They may be in after May 1999. Yet, they must come together now, because only then can it be assured that a relatively smooth process will take place over the next 15 months. \par \par \uc2  The moves on the political front must be seen as the key to an eventual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. It seems that in the near future no moves on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  front can be expected. The IMF recipe will keep us afloat but will not help the recovery. \b \highlight22\uc2 Interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are prohibitively high for the private sector, the real sector as a whole, to do anything significant. \par \par \uc2  Such high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are likely to stay with us for some time. Because, the theory is that the high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will attract capital and in turn will strengthen the currency. Capital is not going to come in so long as the political situation and the security conditions of the country remain precarious as they are now. \par \par \uc2  There is the proposal for the government to adopt a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of providing subsidized credits to selected sectors of production. Aburizal Bakrie, the chairman of Kadin Indonesia, is among those that propose this selective approach. There is some logic in the proposal. Yet, in the present situation such selectivity only tends to reinforce the bad practices of the Soeharto regime and will take us farther away from good governance. \par \par \uc2  Sofyan Wanandi is Chairman and CEO of the widely diversified Gemala Group. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dua1006fd\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
