\par\par \b \uc2  Govt must let foreigners buy property - Analyst. \b0\par\par\uc2 455 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 October 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The government must allow foreigners to own both private and commercial property in Indonesia to help boost the dormant property sector, a property analyst has said. \par \par \uc2  Panangian Simanungkalit said on Thursday that foreigners were potential buyers of property in the country, and this could help local developers and property firms overcome their financial problems. \par \par \uc2  "Foreigners' interest in buying property here is abundant. The only problem is that they face legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in property ownership," Panangian was quoted as saying by Antara on Thursday. \par \par \uc2  In 1996, the government issued a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  allowing foreign companies or foreign nationals, with stay permit cards, to buy a house, an apartment or a condominium. \par \par \uc2  Panangian said the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be amended so that even nonresidents were allowed buy houses. \par \par \uc2  "The only thing they must not be allowed to buy are (government-subsidized) low-cost houses or very cheap houses, and very large plots," he said. \par \par \uc2  Property could be offered to foreign tourists who regularly visit Indonesia, he said. \par \par \uc2  If about 1 percent of the total foreign visitors to the country bought property at an average price of US$100,000, it would add up significantly, he said. \par \par \uc2  Foreign nationals who work in Indonesia, totaling about 60,000 people, are also potential buyers of upmarket properties in the country, he said. \par \par \uc2  Most expatriates do not stay long in a country. Within three to four years, they would most likely sell their property if there were gains to be made, he said. \par \par \uc2  He said, however, that priority should be given to the sale of supermarkets, apartments and condominiums for commercial use to foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  Panangian cited the Golden Triangle commercial district in South Jakarta as being worth over $18.5 billion, out of a total of about $50 billion worth of commercial properties throughout the country. \par \par \uc2  "If foreign investors were to purchase 10 percent of the total $50 billion worth of commercial property, the sector could rake in about $5 billion," he said. \par \par \uc2  The property sector is among the worst hit by the prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis, which has seen the rupiah drop in value by about 70 percent since August last year. \par \par \uc2  While developers are burdened by foreign debts, their markets drop as purchasing power sharply diminishes. \par \par \uc2  Panangian said 80 percent out of about 2,500 developers had technically gone bankrupt or had temporarily suspended operation since the monetary crisis struck. \par \par \uc2  He estimated that the amount of loans that developers had obtained from local banks reached about Rp 75 trillion ($10 billion), while their offshore debts amounted to about Rp 35 trillion, he said. \par \par \uc2  He said developers mostly obtained short-term loans to finance long-term projects. (das) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924duau0034p\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
