\par\par \b \uc2  Bankers call on govt to extend CAR deadline. \b0\par\par\uc2 693 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 November 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  8 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Bankers urged the government on Wednesday to set back the end-of-December deadline for all commercial banks to have a minimum 4 percent capital adequacy ratio (CAR) due to their current difficulty in raising cash. \par \par \uc2  The chairman of the Association of Indonesian Private Commercial Banks (Perbanas) Gunarni Soeworo said that it would be arduous for bank owners to come up with as little as 20 percent of the funding requirement for bank recapitalization. \par \par \uc2  She added that persuading foreign investors to enter the banking sector would be just as hard on account of the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the political situation. \par \par \uc2  "Foreign investors are still watching the political developments here," she said on the sidelines of a seminar on banking. \par \par \uc2  Perbanas held a closed-door meeting to further discuss the government's bank recapitalization program late on Wednesday. \par \par \uc2  The government has required all banks to have a minimum 4 percent CAR requirement by the end of this year, 8 percent by the end of 1999, and 10 percent by the end of 2000. \par \par \uc2  CAR is the ratio between equity capital and risk-weighted assets. \par \par \uc2  The government initially set this year's minimum CAR level at 8 percent, but slashed it in half in the wake of the currency crisis that has continued to devastate the banking industry. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  director Subarjo Joyosumarto said at the seminar that financial audits to check banks' capital condition had almost been completed by late last month as scheduled except on 26 debt-ridden banks currently in the hands of the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency (IBRA). \par \par \uc2  Under the government's bank recapitalization program, banks with CAR levels of between minus 25 percent and plus 4 percent will have to be recapitalized under a system by which the government would provide 80 percent of the funding through the issuance of bonds. \par \par \uc2  Banks with CARs of less than minus 25 percent will be given one month to improve their capital position to qualify for the government funding scheme or face closure. \par \par \uc2  Analysts estimate the recapitalization funding will range between 15 percent and 25 percent of the country's gross domestic product. \par \par \uc2  "I think the government has to delay the minimum capital requirement deadline or make some changes," said Rijanto Sastroatmodjo, a Bank Umum Servitia commissioner, pointing out that the financial audits for the recapitalization were based on the financial conditions in March and that the state of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  had deteriorated since then. \par \par \uc2  He said that most of the country's large banks would not be able to come up with the minimum 20 percent funding because of the current tight liquidity situation. \par \par \uc2  "Only the small and probably some medium banks will qualify for the recapitalization program," he said, pointing to the relatively smaller amount of funding needed for their recapitalization. \par \par \uc2  "Owners of big banks won't be able to participate (in the recapitalization program)," he added. \par \par \uc2  Bank Bumi Putera president Agus Martowardojo concurred. \par \par \uc2  He said that bank owners and foreign investors would not be interested in pouring their money in unless the government set a high coupon rate for the bonds issued for the recapitalization. \par \par \uc2  He pointed out that bankers and investors would be encouraged if the coupon rate was set at 3 percent above the benchmark interest rate of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's one-month promisory note. \par \par \uc2  "But this will be a very huge burden for the taxpayers," he added. \par \par \uc2  The government will issue bonds to finance 80 percent of the bank recapitalization program, in which the government will only inject fresh money amounting to the bond coupon rate. \par \par \uc2  The banks will have to provide the government with nonvoting shares for the bonds, which will be redeemable by the bank owners in three years or sold on to new investors before the government takes over. \par \par \uc2  The government has yet to decide the coupon rate. \par \par \uc2  Bank owners had earlier proposed an injection of fixed assets to boost their capital condition, but this was apparently rejected by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "We want cash. Without that what's the use of recapitalization," \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Governor Sjahril Sabirin demanded. (rei) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dub50012j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
