\par\par \b \uc2  Unrest may derail RI recovery. \b0\par\par\uc2 532 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 November 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  12 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The deadly protests and riots shaking the city last week would derail \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in the country, experts said on Tuesday. \par \par \uc2  Sri Mulyani Indrawati, an economist at the University of Indonesia, said the bloody protests and riots had created market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially for foreign investors. \par \par \uc2  "It shows that Indonesia is not stable and carries high political risks," Sri added. \par \par \uc2  She said private funds, which were badly needed to drive Indonesia out of the crisis, would not come until political and legal certainty was restored. \par \par \uc2  However, Sri criticized the government's repressive actions against dissidents in a move to pursue political stability. \par \par \uc2  "Stability created through such repressive measures would be vulnerable. It would not be strong enough to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery." \par \par \uc2  "Therefore, the government should solve various pressing political problems using sustainable and civilized political mechanisms." \par \par \uc2  She said that the government was too optimistic in its prediction that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would improve in the first half of 1999 as stated in its letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , she said, would not bottom out until the second semester of 1999, considering various political events like general elections in the middle of next year, the convening of the People's Consultative Assembly and various factors affecting the decision-making process of a new government. \par \par \uc2  "It would be safe to say that our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would likely book positive growth in the first semester of year 2000." \par \par \uc2  Nevertheless, IMF Asia Pacific director Hubert Neiss said continued political unrest in Indonesia may have a negative impact on the country's shaky \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  He noted, however, that he still saw "significant scope" for the rupiah to strengthen, despite the unrest. \par \par \uc2  "We have to see if the (political) \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues for a while," Neiss said. In that case, "it will affect expectations and may have an unfavorable impact (on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery)." \par \par \uc2  "To me personally, the main damage of the last few days has been the loss of life and the reduction of confidence," Neiss told Dow Jones Newswires. \par \par \uc2  Deadly protests and riots shook the Indonesian capital on Friday. At least 15 people, including seven students, were killed when the military turned on student protesters. \par \par \uc2  The violence was the worst in Jakarta since May, when much heavier rioting swept the city and helped unseat President Soeharto after three decades in power. \par \par \uc2  Neiss said the impact on the rupiah will depend on how long investors see the unrest continuing. \par \par \uc2  "If they think it's the beginning of a prolonged period of instability, then it would affect the exchange rate and capital would flow out," Neiss said. If the unrest proves temporary, Indonesia's improved \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance should help the currency, he added. \par \par \uc2  "On the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  side, all things point to further strengthening (of the rupiah)," Neiss said. \par \par \uc2  He noted that inflation has been falling rapidly, the current account surplus is substantial, official aid is flowing in and the budgetary situation has improved markedly. \par \par \uc2  He praised the country's compliance with its IMF program. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance has been exemplary," Neiss said. "By now, it has sunk in that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is firmly on track." \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dubi001f6\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
