\par\par \b \uc2  Foreign investors remain reluctant to enter RI banks. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Reiner S. \par \uc2 906 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 November 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  10 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Foreign investors will not enter Indonesia's cash-strapped banking sector if \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fields continues, according to a foreign fund manager. \par \par \uc2  Gerry Grimstone, vice chairman of the London-based fund management firm Schroders said foreign investors wouldn't channel the massive amount of fresh money needed to recapitalize the country's ailing banking sector unless the risk of investing here could be measured. \par \par \uc2  He said that political and currency stability, as well as consistency in government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  were the key factors in attracting foreign investors to enter Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "I think once the foreigners understand what the future looks like, there will be the appetite here. But at the moment they find it very hard to estimate the risk. They can't work out whether something is worth 100 or 10. Once they can understand the risk, I wouldn't be surprised if they wanted to invest here," he told The Jakarta Post in an interview on Friday after speaking at the Indonesia Forum business conference. \par \par \uc2  Schroders is among the largest foreign investors in the country's capital market with outstanding total investments of around US$1 billion. \par \par \uc2  The sharp depreciation of the rupiah against the U.S. dollar has sent the Indonesian banking sector into a tailspin. \par \par \uc2  The government has injected more than Rp 140 trillion (US$18 billion) to help troubled banks meet withdrawals made by panicked depositors in the wake of plunging confidence. It is now trying hard to get back the money by selling the fixed assets in the form of various companies surrendered by owners of the banks. \par \par \uc2  The government has also pledged to provide 80 percent of the financing needed to recapitalize the banking sector to meet the minimum 4 percent capital adequacy ratio requirement by the end of this year. \par \par \uc2  Part of the recapitalization measures would be to takeover the massive volume of banks non-performing loans, which would be repackaged before selling them to investors. \par \par \uc2  The government has said that it would issue bonds to recapitalize the banking sector, which would be sold to investors in three to five years time. \par \par \uc2  Grimstone estimated that some $13-19 billion in new capital would be needed to recapitalize the Indonesian banking sector. \par \par \uc2  "The problem is the only sources at present for the money are trade and portfolio investors, vulture funds, the Indonesian government and multilateral agencies," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Foreign investment is a vital component, but it requires political and currency stability," he added. \par \par \uc2  Violent clashes between student protesters and security officials reemerged on November 13, followed by looting and arson the next day in Jakarta, as a manifestation of widespread protests over the country's slow political reform. The bloody clashes caused deep concern among investors over the country's political stability, which became unstable following the killing of students, rioting, looting, and arson in May which led to the downfall of former president Soeharto. The country is planning to have a general election next year. \par \par \uc2  Although the rupiah has considerably strengthened to around Rp 7,500 to the dollar, compared to Rp 14,000 in June, many say the currency remains volatile due to a combination of political instability and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  factors. \par \par \uc2  "The questions people often ask are ' where is the bedrock, when can we know that things won't get any worse in Indonesia? When is the stability coming back?' I think the politicians, business leaders and all who are concerned for the future of Indonesia have to look for that bedrock," Grimstone said. \par \par \uc2  He also said that a consistent government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was an important ingredient in reviving the shattered financial sector. \par \par \uc2  "Indonesia needs strong and consistent leadership in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  management to get out of its current position," he said, pointing out that government \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be clear and realistic. \par \par \uc2  The way the government handled the repayment of the more than Rp 140 trillion in liquidity support injected into troubled banks was a good example. \par \par \uc2  President B.J. Habibie initially demanded bankers return the money in cash in one year, but this was seen as unrealistic by the bankers, so it was then extended to four years following pressure by the IMF. Demands from certain people in the political elite to use the fixed assets, surrendered by the bankers to repay their obligations, as a means of wealth distribution has increased the obscurity of these matters. \par \par \uc2  Grimstone also said that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data must be timely, reliable and widely circulated to give rise to confidence in the country because people could then see the real picture of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  "I think more can be done here in terms of circulation of reliable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  information," he said. \par \par \uc2  "The capital market won't return to Indonesia unless confidence is created," he added. \par \par \uc2  "But the good news is that we have found multinational corporations are already interested in Indonesia as they see a great future here, but not many are willing to invest immediately as they're studying the situation," he said. \par \par \uc2  He explained that a proper implementation of the country's privatization program would be a very important ingredient in reviving foreign investors confidence. \par \par \uc2  "I think it is very important for the privatization program of Indonesia to move away from the concept of individual sales to be much more of a program for reaching macro-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  objectives," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dubn001ka\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
