\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah's growth lacks fundamental support. \b0\par\par\uc2 813 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 November 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  The rupiah has remained strong in spite of the political upheaval during the recent Special Session of the People's Consultative Assembly. Raden Pardede, a senior economist at the state-owned securities company PT Danareksa, discusses the factors supporting the currency's strength. \par \par \uc2  Question: Do you think the recent strengthening of the rupiah reflects improvements in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals or has it instead been supported by the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's market intervention? \par \par \uc2  Pardede: The rupiah is strengthening not because of improvement in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals but due to external factors and the intervention of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) or, more accurately, the government. \par \par \uc2  The external factors include the recent decline in U.S. \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the fall of the U.S. dollar against other major currencies. Internally, the government has been selling its foreign aid funds to obtain rupiah for its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The government has repeatedly denied any market intervention, but market players believe that its dollar sales have an impact similar to intervention. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's sales of about US$10 million to $30 million nearly every day have a great impact on the country's thin money market, with a daily volume of only between $50 million and $100 million. \par \par \uc2  The only fundamental factor supporting the rupiah is the decline in the inflation rate. \par \par \uc2  Q: Will the rupiah's value likely remain stable at the current level of about Rp 7,500 per dollar? \par \par \uc2  P: No. The rupiah's exchange rate depends on the supply-demand condition on the foreign exchange market, while our dollar supplies are now relying too much on the disbursement of foreign aid. We cannot expect much from exports, which are leveling off as international oil prices are declining and demand for other Indonesian products is weakening due to the slower growth of the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Worse still, capital inflows will not likely occur within the next few months due to political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Q: How can share prices on the stock exchange increase while the rupiah is strengthening? \par \par \uc2  P: The recent decreases in \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's promissory notes (SBIs) and the decline in inflation have encouraged investors to reallocate their funds into shares. \par \par \uc2  Q: How can you say that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamental factors are not improving? \par \par \uc2  P: The current account of our balance of payments, for example, is still performing poorly due to the huge \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the international trade of services, notably freight and tourism. \par \par \uc2  Our commodity trade gains a big surplus not because of a significant rise in exports but because of a sharp decline in our imports. Oil and gas export revenues have been declining due to price falls while other export earnings have been expanding only by about 3 percent. That means that our total export revenue is leveling off. \par \par \uc2  Q: How do you see the domestic supply of goods? \par \par \uc2  P: The supply of basic commodities is adequate at affordable prices thanks to imports and price \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But the question is for how long the government can afford such huge \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 . However, the supply of manufactured consumer goods is declining by more than 50 percent from the precrisis level. \par \par \uc2  The fact that the banking industry has virtually stopped new lendings and imports have fallen to a minimum level further indicate that the production and trading sectors are not moving well. \par \par \uc2  Q: How about the money supply? \par \par \uc2  P: Large \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  have caused the money supply to surge nominally (to Rp 540.86 trillion as of August from Rp 325.91 trillion a year earlier, according to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) but in the real term, the money supply is declining due to the sharp depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar - the dollar was quoted at about Rp 2,700 in August 1997 and at about Rp 10,000 in August 1998. Furthermore, most of the money in circulation has gone toward the purchases of SBIs and inter-bank transactions, not to productive activities. \par \par \uc2  Q: What developments do you expect in consumer prices? \par \par \uc2  P: I project that the inflation rate, which exceeded 75 percent during the January-October period, is likely to increase by 2 or 3 percentage points in December. Next year's inflation rate may reach 15 percent, far higher than the government's projection of 10 percent. \par \par \uc2  Q: What about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth? \par \par \uc2  P: The gross domestic product (GDP), which shrank by 13.59 percent during the first nine months of 1998, may contract by 15.5 percent for the whole year. In 1999, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is likely to experience a zero percent growth or a contraction of 2 percent. \par \par \uc2  But a zero percent growth does not necessarily mean the start of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery because this would require a GDP growth of at least 8 percent after a contraction of 15.5 percent this year. (riz) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dubn001kg\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Foreign investors aware on RI politics. \b0\par\par\uc2 617 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 November 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Foreign investors are hesitant to come to Indonesia so long as the political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation remains unstable, despite the country's strong drawing power in the form of natural resources for long-term investment, said Harvey Goldstein, the chairman of the investment consultancy firm Harvey International. \par \par \uc2  But he added that investors would soon come here again once the situation has improved. \par \par \uc2  "Remember, Indonesia is rich in natural resources, which is attractive for long-term investment," he said here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the chairman of Keidanren [the Japanese chamber of commerce and industry], Takashi Imai, yesterday said here that the political development here is currently less favorable due to riots. \par \par \uc2  "There are riots happening here, but that President B.J. Habibie in a meeting with us said that the process of democracy is currently taking place in Indonesia." \par \par \uc2  However, Imai added, Japanese businessmen have pledged not to run away from Indonesia, and that in fact they plan to boost their investment here. \par \par \uc2  As an example, he cited the underground train and electric train projects connecting Jakarta with Surabaya, which he said will proceed as it has been approved by the government. \par \par \uc2  "The interest rate is low at 0.75% per year for 40 years," said the head of the Indonesian chamber of commerce (Kadin Indonesia), Aburizal Bakrie, who went along with the Keidanren delegation in a meeting with President B.J. Habibie here yesterday. \par \par \uc2  As the period leading to the elections in May next year could be alarming, he said "the government has asked Japanese to postpone their plans to visit for holidays." \par \par \uc2  "But there is no limitation for business visits." \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, US-based company Seagate Technology Ltd. has cancelled its plan to build an integrated electronic component plant worth Rp10 trillion in Medan due to political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  here. \par \par \uc2  An official in Medan, Papo Hermawan, confirmed the cancellation, saying that the company has moved out to the Philippines. \par \par \uc2  "They were worried over the political situation here and have now moved to Subic, the Philippines," he said on the sidelines of a ceremony marking the operations of PT Pacific Medan Industri by Investment Minister Hamzah Haz in Medan yesterday. \par \par \uc2  Seagate was one of the six companies that received a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  holiday as it complied with the government ruling PP No. 45/1996. \par \par \uc2  It had planned to absorb at least 10,000 workers. \par \par \uc2  Lippo Securities economist Martin P.H. Panggabean, lamented the departure of Seagate from Indonesia, telling Bisnis that "it could serve as a precedent if the present crisis is not overcome." \par \par \uc2  He was surprised by Seagate's decision as it had made a quite large initial investment in Medan and that the city fitted into its plan to penetrate the Asian market such as Cyberjaya [Malaysia] and Singapore \par \par \uc2  "Seagate realized that prospects here now and next year are dim." \par \par \uc2  The poor situation has also been blamed by Haz as the reason behind foreign investors' reluctance to come here, as well as their decision to postpone or cancel their projects. \par \par \uc2  Between January and October, he pointed out, the level of foreign and domestic investment has dropped by 40% over the same period last year. \par \par \uc2  Hamzah said that what is needed now is large number of projects, and not the value of the investments so that many jobs could be created. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, forestry-related businessmen grouped under MPI predicted that investment in the sector next year will drop by about 70% or US$1.75 billion over last year's figures of US$2.5 billion. \par \par \uc2  MPI chief Sudradjat Djaja P. said that foreigners would only enter Indonesia after the general and presidential elections next year. (ab/ram/san/ea). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922dubp0015d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  Student demonstrations help investors' confidence. \b0\par\par\uc2 342 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 November 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Student demonstrations are expected to have positive impact on foreign investors' confidence in the capital market since the actions are expected to lead to improvement in all aspects of life. \par \par \uc2  "The fleeing of foreigners from Indonesia has not been due to fear of student demonstrations but rather to torture and massive looting by the masses," said a capital market analyst Hasan Zein. \par \par \uc2  Hasan said at the Jakarta Dialog Forum Thursday night that student demonstrations could in fact build confidence among foreign investors that the actions will improve the control system that has been weak. \par \par \uc2  He said it is the excess of the demonstrations that need to be minimized rather than the students' demands. "It is strange to me that orderly student demonstrations receive heavy guard while during looting we hardly see any troops." \par \par \uc2  Although \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  clouds the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , he said, the future of the capit