\par\par \b \uc2  Rupiah steady but stocks down further. \b0\par\par\uc2 484 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 November 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The rupiah remained steady at 7,450 against the U.S. dollar on Friday, but stock prices in the local exchange continued declining. \par \par \uc2  Currency dealers said the rupiah, which opened at 7,300, rose to an intraday high of 7,250 during midday trading due to heavy dollar-selling by offshore operators across the region. \par \par \uc2  They said that market participants, especially from Singapore and Hong Kong, unloaded their dollar holdings for rupiah. \par \par \uc2  "Overseas operators wanted to square their position," a chief dealer with a local private bank said. \par \par \uc2  Dealers said, however, that an unexpected dollar bid by state banks in late trading drove the rupiah down to end the week at 7,450. \par \par \uc2  "I think the state banks bought dollars for their customers to settle their overseas debts or to finance imports," the dealer said, pointing out that trading volume had significantly declined now. \par \par \uc2  In the past several days, state banks were seen actively selling dollars - a move which analyst said was made on behalf of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , to prop up the rupiah. \par \par \uc2  "The rupiah is expected to advance to the 7,000 level to the dollar next week," another dealer said. \par \par \uc2  Unlike the rupiah, share prices on the local shattered market fell nearly 1 percent on Friday due to persistent profit taking on big capitalized stocks which booked gains the previous days. \par \par \uc2  The Composite Index, the main price gauge on the Jakarta Stock Exchange, fell 2.35 points to 392.32, with 410 million shares worth Rp 288.81 billion (US$38.76 million) changing hands. \par \par \uc2  Decliners outpaced gainers by 60 to 37 with 88 stocks remaining unchanged. \par \par \uc2  Brokers said the fall of some regional equity markets coupled with massive profit taking on most blue chip stocks had weighed down market sentiment in the local bourse. \par \par \uc2  "But on top of that, profit ahead of the weekend was behind the decline of the local market," Vonny Juwono, an institutional sale broker with Trimegah Securindolestari, said. \par \par \uc2  Head of research of Sigma Batara Fadjar Limin Sutandi said that global and regional funds, which entered the local bourse last week, were no longer tempted to stay in the battered market due to lingering and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the country. \par \par \uc2  Trimegah's Vonny said foreign brokerage firms, which put in more selling orders to cash in profits on Friday, included Jardine Fleming, ING Barings Securities and ABN Amro. \par \par \uc2  But she said other foreign investors continued to place more buying orders through WI Carr Securities Indonesia, Credit Lyonnais Indonesia and Merryl Lynch Indonesia in the local exchange. \par \par \uc2  Several blue chip stocks ended lower, with state international call operator PT Indosat sliding Rp 250 to Rp 10,900, pulp firm PT Tjiwi Kimia shed Rp 50 to Rp 1,650 and mining firm PT Aneka Tambang fell Rp 25 to Rp 1,650. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924dubs001pz\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\uc2  - SBI rates to reach 30% by March '99. \b0\par\par\uc2 708 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 November 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  director Miranda Swaray Goeltom has said that the rates of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  certificates (SBI) may reach 37% by the end of 1998 and 30% by March 1999. \par \par \uc2  "The current rate is 46%, but I'm certain by the end of the year the figure would be about 37% and 30% by March 1999. As such banks' negative spread would become positive again. If that would be the case, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would automatically move again," Miranda told Bisnis here last week. \par \par \uc2  Miranda's optimism is based on the results of the weekly SBI auction, which has been showing a downward trend. \par \par \uc2  Last week the SBI rate reached 46.42%, down from 49.66% the week before. \par \par \uc2  "I'm sure the rate would reach 42% next week." \par \par \uc2  A SBI rate of 30% in March next year could re-activate bank credits, she said, "as lending rates would then be about 35%." \par \par \uc2  "At the same time the restructurization and recapitalization programs could proceed as well." \par \par \uc2  She said that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  can always lower the rates to below 46.42% this week. \par \par \uc2  "But we have to take into account many indicators and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The main thing is that the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would raise hope of recovery although the results would not be that quick." \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, BI has again lowered the rates for time deposits by 3 points to 49% for the 30 November-6 December 1998 period. \par \par \uc2  Bisnis noted that this is the first time in the past six months that the rate has been set at below 50%. \par \par \uc2  Since the rate reached its peak at 67%, BI has reduced the rate by 18% in six weeks. \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  official Kusumaningtuti S.S., in a recent press release, said that the rates for time deposits for 2-24 months have been lowered by 2%-3%. \par \par \uc2  For time deposits of three months the rate is 47% (down by 3%), six months 38% (down 2%), 12 months 36% (down 2%), and 24 months down 3% to 25%. \par \par \uc2  BI has also lowered the rates for dollar time deposits for 24 months by 1% to 17%. \par \par \uc2  For one month the rate remains at 15%, while for three, six and 12 months the rate is 14%. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, the capital of state banks (BUMNs) is known to have dropped by 94% to only Rp1.039 trillion between June and September as a result of their negative spread and forex loses. \par \par \uc2  Towil Heryoto, the former CEO of Bapindo, said that the drop is likely to have been caused by losses incurred during the monetary crisis. \par \par \uc2  "If a bank is profitable, it would be impossible for its capital to be eroded." \par \par \uc2  Towil said that in general bad loans, negative spread and forex losses do not cause banks to suffer losses. \par \par \uc2  "But because of the prolonged crisis, the loss could eat into its capital." \par \par \uc2  He noted that up to June 1998 state banks still enjoyed profits. \par \par \uc2  "So the drop is likely to have occurred in July, August and September." \par \par \uc2  According to the monthly report of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the most drastic drop took place in June and July, from Rp18.541 trillion to Rp2.215 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Towil suspects that the drop in state banks' capital from Rp21 trillion [May 1998] to Rp1.039 trillion [September] was due to the forex loss suffered by Bank Exim at Rp20 trillion. \par \par \uc2  "My feeling is that the capital in other state banks is still positive." \par \par \uc2  Towil said that the recapitalization scheme - in which the government is prepared to fund 80% of the required amount - shows that the government is aware of the real banking situation. \par \par \uc2  Bank Bali director Rusli Suryadi said that since the steep appreciation of the rupiah, banks' forex debts have risen dramatically "while at the same time banks' capital are wholly in rupiah." \par \par \uc2  "This causes a drop in the capital of banks as banks would have to set aside large amounts of credit \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  because of poor credit collection due to the monetary crisis." \par \par \uc2  "So the idea to allow banks here to have capital in forex is worth considering," he said on the sidelines of the seminar "Winning in crisis" last week. (m2/ind/dj/ab/gps). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922dubu0016n\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2  'Unsustainable capital inflow impedes  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  recovery'. \b0\par\par\uc2 183 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 November 1998\par \uc2 Bisnis Indonesia\par \uc2 BISNIS\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia\par \par \uc2  Indonesia and other Asian crisis-ridden countries still face unsustainable inflow of foreign capital, leaving their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  turning points 'not permanent', said noted economist M. Nawir Messi. \par \par \uc2  He noted that the turning point, which is marked by the countries' stronger currencies, falling prices and lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are not permanent in nature because of their strong dependence on foreign capital. \par \par \uc2  "The problem in Asia is unsustainable capital inflow," he said in a seminar on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  here last week. \par \par \uc2  The problem is due to political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which he said figures high in the minds of foreign investors in their decision to invest in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  "The Semanggi tragedy had a deep impact on efforts to restore foreign confidence." \par \par \uc2  Even before the incident took place, said Messi, foreign investors were already factoring in political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to the general and presidential elections next year. \par \par \uc2  "Say the elections went well, we do not have any idea what the new government looks like, what its agenda and where the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be heading to", he said. (ab). \par \par \uc2  (c) 1998 Bisnis Indonesia. \par \par \uc2 Document bisnis0020010922dubu0016r\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
