\par\par \b \uc2  Bearish stock market seen continuing. \b0\par\par\uc2 597 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 December 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  11 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Share prices of the country's stock market will remain bearish next year as worries over the country's social and political prospects will continue to discourage investors, according to analysts. \par \par \uc2  Stock market analyst Hasan Zein Mahmud said on Thursday that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the country's political format and possible worsening of the social and security situations would continue to cast a shadow across the capital market's activities. \par \par \uc2  He said that the key factor would be determined by the political atmosphere before and after the general election, which is scheduled for June of next year. \par \par \uc2  "If the general election runs smoothly and all respect its results, the capital market bull will come back," Hasan, the former president of the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX), said in a seminar held by the Capital Market Journalists Club (CMJC). \par \par \uc2  But he warned that if the election did not run as expected and many party members went on the streets to protest the election results, the country's capital market would plunge to its worst levels yet. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian government is scheduled to hold a general election on June 7 next year, followed by the general session of the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) on Nov. 30 to elect a new president and vice president. \par \par \uc2  Analysts said they were worried the general election would not solve the problem and that the antigovernment protests, which have taken place almost every day since May, would instead escalate. \par \par \uc2  Hasan said that another contributory factor to the bearish stock market outlook next year was the worsening of the financial performance of companies listed in the stock exchange. \par \par \uc2  He said that around 90 percent of the total 289 listed firms in the local market suffered massive losses as the impact of the country's worst ever crisis was fully felt. \par \par \uc2  The crisis, triggered by the plunge of the rupiah, could worsen if the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovering measures failed to solve the existing problems, he said. \par \par \uc2  "If it happens, no one will come to the country to do business and as a consequence Indonesia could further plunge to zero," other analyst said. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah, which is hovering around 7,500, has lost almost 60 percent of its value against the U.S. dollar since the crisis first hit the country in August during which the rupiah was about 2,500 against the American greenback. \par \par \uc2  Unlike Hasan, JSX president Cyril D Noerhadi said that despite such a gloomy outlook, some investors would still be tempted to enter the local market to benefit from cheap stocks. \par \par \uc2  He said that though political turmoil had swept the country in 1998, daily transactions value in the local bourse had declined slightly to Rp 417 billion in the period compared to Rp 489 billion in 1997. \par \par \uc2  Daily trading volume, however, increased significantly to around 378 million shares per day in 1998 compared to 311 million shares the previous year, he said. \par \par \uc2  "This shows that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis has not adversely affected our local market," he said Thursday. \par \par \uc2  JSX's Composite Index rose 1.2 percent on Thursday to end the day at 403.66 with 261.13 million shares worth Rp 201.89 billion changing hands. \par \par \uc2  Stock brokers attributed the slight increase to selective program buying on certain blue-chip stocks to benefit from the easing of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the banking system. \par \par \uc2  Taking the lead in the share prices, the rupiah remained steady closing unbudged at 7,500 in light trading against the U.S. dollar on Thursday. (aly) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924ducb0024b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
