\par\par \b \uc2  National consensus needed to avoid more serious chaos. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Laksamana Sukardi \par \uc2 1,885 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 December 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  5 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  This is the second of two articles analyzing the current crisis in Indonesia and predicting the outcome in the near future. \par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The many instances of blatant state-sponsored terrorism have finally made the people, who are already suffering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship, commit counter-acts of lawlessness. These problems cannot be solved without a legitimate government chosen by the people and independent of the Soeharto regime. Only such a government will be capable of upholding law and order in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  The polarization of political parties and the possibility of coalitions. \par \par \uc2  The process of transition that is threatening national integration is forged further by the weakness of the transitional government, the unstable condition of ABRI and political radicalization aimed at sectarian politics. There is a polarization of political parties into two camps, namely: 1) Pluralist parties that are open and seen as nationalistic; and 2) Sectarian parties that are exclusive and divisive. Therefore, the coalitions that may be formed after the general election will be coalitions of those parties that are pluralist and a coalition of the divisive parties. \par \par \uc2  The attitude of ABRI is still unclear, as is the fate of the Golongan Karya (Soeharto's ruling party). Will they support the divisive or the pluralist camps? The reform within Golkar and the renewal of ABRI leadership will have a strong impact on the political direction taken by these two forces and in determining which political coalition will win in the coming election. \par \par \uc2  Different from the rising radicalization of politics and state-sponsored terrorism, the opposition leaders in Indonesia have clearly manifested a very moderate stance. The Ciganjur Declaration, which was signed by four opposition leaders (Abdurrahman Wahid, Amien Rais, Sri Sultan Hamengkubuwono X and Megawati Soekarnoputri) during the Special Session of the MPR, is notably moderate. \par \par \uc2  The opposition leaders have widespread grassroots support but clearly desire a peaceful and phased transition. For this reason, they have acknowledged Habibie's as a legitimate transitional government until the general elections are held and have agreed to the elimination in stages of ABRI's dual function. Their attitude was adamantly challenged by the students who want Habibie to immediately resign to be replaced by an interim presidium council. The student groups are also demanding the immediate elimination of ABRI's role in Indonesian politics. \par \par \uc2  We can conclude that there is a split in the opposition, namely: 1) the moderate opposition or Ciganjur camp; and 2) the moral opposition, represented by the student movement. These two camps are closely aligned in their views concerning democracy in Indonesia, except for technical differences and their \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  demanding a brief transition. However, these differences can add to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and instability of the process of transition in Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  Business prospects and conditions in Indonesia are linked closely to political developments. The process of transition from the authoritarian regime led by Soeharto to democracy is full of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The process of transition has caused a constitutional crisis that has resulted in a series of riots and bloody clashes. This chaos has directly disrupted business activities and the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The transition government of President Habibie lacks credibility. The business community and foreign investors are forced to accept this reality. Consequently, the government is unable to take a firm stance and is often seen as flip-flopping with regard to its policies. The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  has made it clear in mass protests that it does not feel represented by the present government. \par \par \uc2  Besides the lack of legitimacy on the part of the government, other factors that greatly hinder the recovery of business in Indonesia, include: \par \par \uc2  1. Problems with the banking system: \par \par \uc2  The restructuring of the banking system in Indonesia still faces extremely daunting obstacles. The partial approach in the restructuring of the banking system (in which the state banks have not been touched by reform) will not restore the confidence of the international banking community. In fact, all of the banks in Indonesia are currently insolvent and this has hindered business and investment from running normally. \par \par \uc2  2. The debt overhang: \par \par \uc2  There has been no workable, fair, and systematic solution for dealing with the matter of Indonesia's huge private foreign debt. This debt overhang is undermining the capacity of Indonesian businesses to operate. \par \par \uc2  3. Legal certainty: \par \par \uc2  The government has canceled foreign investment projects that seemed to be tainted with corruption, collusion and nepotism. There have been protests and disruptions of investment projects in several regions because the local people are angry about being left out or have suffered actual losses due to the approval of these investment projects. These cases have caused businesses and foreign investors to have a very circumspect attitude. \par \par \uc2  4. Country risk: \par \par \uc2  The severe collapse in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the parallel instabilities in the political realm, as well as widespread perceptions of mismanagement of the banking crisis, debt overhang, and problems with legal commitments on the part of the government all converge to make Indonesia a high-risk environment for investment. Even those adventurous foreign investors who might want to take all the risks find that it is extremely difficult to get foreign financing because of Indonesia's unfavorable country risk. \par \par \uc2  In light of the current problems and overall conditions, it is obvious that Indonesia needs to establish policies that will increase the confidence of the world business community. Vital \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms that must be implemented immediately to increase confidence include: \par \par \uc2  1. Independent judiciary system: \par \par \uc2  To guarantee legal certainty and justice for the business community, an independent judiciary system must be in place. The judiciary process must not be subject to intervention by those in power. Only then can all types of dispute be settled justly and clearly. In this way the business community will operate transparently and competitively, without certain businessmen with connections getting preferential treatment. \par \par \uc2  2. Empowerment of democratic institutions: All strategic policies involve the people at large through democratic institutions. Then the possibility of protests that can disrupt approved investment projects or business licenses can be avoided. One reason for the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about and loss of confidence in Indonesia is that these institutions (parliament, political parties and the general election committees) do not function properly. The people feel these government policies and investment licenses should be revoked. \par \par \uc2  3. Clean government: \par \par \uc2  The government must change its attitude to ensure that all policies are implemented smoothly and have the support of the masses. To accomplish this, the government must be clean and free from conflict of interest. These criteria must be fulfilled in order to restore the confidence of the business world and foreign investors so they will invest again in Indonesia. A clean government is also absolutely essential to do away with high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  costs. \par \par \uc2  There is wide potential that the social and political conditions in Indonesia as we approach the General Election and during it in June 1999 will spur further rioting and conflict between the various camps. \par \par \uc2  Several important variables will determine the degree of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the election period, including: \par \par \uc2  1. Developments within ABRI and Golkar. It is yet to be seen if these two organizations will transform themselves from within or if they will be forced to by external pressures. The most important question is whether ABRI and Golkar will be able to maintain their pluralism or alternatively become supporters of the move toward political radicalization and sectarian politics. \par \par \uc2  2. Deliberations by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) concerning the draft political laws (elections, political parties and the composition of state institutions). If the laws are representative of the people's aspirations, then the level of chaos during the elections can be reduced. But if the laws are in conflict with these democratic aspirations, then it is certain the election will be volatile due to the intensity of clashes and lawlessness. \par \par \uc2  Whatever happens within ABRI and Golkar and with the election laws, it is almost inevitable that the coming election will be marked by social unrest stemming from physical clashes between the various camps and political parties due to the increasingly heated political atmosphere and exacerbated further by the pressures of a prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis. Other factors that contribute to troubles during the election period, include: \par \par \uc2  1. The ineffectiveness of ABRI and its leadership. \par \par \uc2  2. The further radicalization of politics and fundamentalist religious sentiments supported by the government (for example: the use of vigilante volunteers to safeguard the Special Session of the MPR; the comments of Minister of Food AM Saefuddin concerning religion and the president; and others). \par \par \uc2  3. The ineffective functioning of the government due to its lack of mandate from the people. In addition, the Habibie government's image as just a continuation of the blatantly corrupt regime of Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  4. The many cases of human rights abuses that have wounded the hearts of the people. These cases have never been settled in court and include the shooting of students, the abduction of activists, particularly those who are still missing, the investigation into the corruption of the Soeharto regime, the accusations of treason by certain key opposition figures, the brutality of ABRI in Aceh, East Timor and Irian Jaya, the follow up to investigations of the May 1998 riots, the attack on the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) headquarters on July 27, 1996, the murder of Marsinah, the misappropriation of farmers' land and many others. \par \par \uc2  5. The wave of protest against the government will continue to swell as the people lose patience in the Habibie government and its inability to prosecute Soeharto for corruption. President Habibie will try to postpone the prosecution of Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  6. Those of the "status quo" will make desperate attempts to win the election by whatever means. They fear if they lose then they will likely be brought to court for their part in Soeharto's empire of corruption. \par \par \uc2  7. The prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis and increased demand by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  for necessities to celebrate both the Islamic Lebaran and Christmas holidays. There could be natural disasters spurred by La Nia that could add to the turbulent political scene as we approach the election. \par \par \uc2  Social, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political conditions in Indonesia during the transition to total reform are very fragile and unstable. Therefore, only a democratic \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  election that is open and fair can solve these problems faced by the people of Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  A democratic election will solve the extremely complex constitutional crisis and quickly guarantee the legitimacy and credibility of the government and the government's mandate from the people will no longer be debated. On the way, the government can function effectively in carrying out programs aimed at \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. \par \par \uc2  To reduce the possibility of more dangerous social unrest during and after the elections, a greater national consensus is vitally needed to achieve national reconciliation. The consensus must include all of the various components of society and must be achieved prior to the elections. \par \par \uc2  If a consensus is not achieved, then sadly, it is highly likely that the coming election will become volatile and riots could easily tear the nation apart even further. On the other hand, if a national consensus is achieved, then recovery in every field will accelerate and Indonesia's recovery could also expedite a faster recovery of regional economies. \par \par \uc2  The writer is chief executive officer of ReFORM consulting based in Jakarta. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924ducf002ao\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
