\par\par \b \uc2  Juwono warns against too much freedom. \b0\par\par\uc2 481 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 December 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  1 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Minister of Education and Culture Juwono Sudarsono said on Wednesday the country had gone too far too fast in its search for political freedom and called for some restrictions to minimize the possibility of bloodshed during the June general election. \par \par \uc2  Juwono said he had asked the government to ban outdoor rallies and restrict campaigning to indoors in the run-up to the June 7 poll. \par \par \uc2  "I have asked the home affairs minister (Syarwan Hamid) to consider our recommendations... that campaigning should be limited to closed \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  buildings and that street rallies should be banned," he told a meeting of the Indonesia-Australia Business Council. \par \par \uc2  The council invited Juwono to speak on the current social and political events. \par \par \uc2  People hope the June election and a subsequent presidential election will usher in a new era of democracy and freedom in the nation after 32-years of autocratic, army-backed rule by former president Soeharto. \par \par \uc2  Pushed by growing demands for political reform, his successor, President B.J. Habibie, promised to hold general and presidential elections in 1999 instead of waiting until 2003, when the nation was next scheduled to go to the polls. \par \par \uc2  But Juwono said that civil strife in recent months showed that Indonesia still lacked the necessary social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundations for political freedom. \par \par \uc2  "The pendulum has swung too far in favor of political openness," Juwono said. \par \par \uc2  Juwono said that the nation was "perhaps moving from the Chinese model of government to the Indian model of democracy". \par \par \uc2  "(We are moving) from a period when the government was centralized with very firm control exercised through the military, the bureaucracy and one dominant political party, toward one that will be very open, very loose and very unfocused. \par \par \uc2  "I am of course more pessimistic than my colleagues...because I have seen in the past few months that in that respect I think perhaps we have gone too far too fast. \par \par \uc2  "The desire for political democracy and openness is juxtaposed with a period of endemic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  deprivation. I think that combination is about the most dangerous possible for political stability." \par \par \uc2  Juwono said that intermittent violence between ethnic and religious groups was inevitable when a country was in a period of transition, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and had wide \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disparities. \par \par \uc2  Juwono also said that he would "persuade" Habibie to reconsider banning students from studying abroad before the age of 18 to prevent their national ties and loyalties from being eroded. \par \par \uc2  "(But in the 1989 law on national education) I do not see any article that specifically bans students from studying abroad...so based on the letter of the law...my own feeling is that I could perhaps persuade the President to reconsider (the ban)." \par \par \uc2  Citing a cartoon in Kompas daily, Juwono pointed out that Habibie and one of his sons were both educated in Germany. (byg) \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924duch002fu\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
