\par\par \b \uc2  The  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  outlook. \b0\par\par\uc2 718 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 December 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  4 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  Though all key \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators have, of late, been showing a marked improvement, never, over the past 30 years, have we been as worried as now, facing a new year with so grave a sense of foreboding about our future. We are leaving a year of political turbulence, increasingly frequent civil strife and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  depression, only to enter a new year pregnant with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in almost all aspects of our life. \par \par \uc2  The political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has been looming since the fall of Soeharto in May seems to make \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  projection and analysis rather irrelevant. As most analysts noted in this paper's year-end \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  review, whatever realistic assumptions are made, they will ultimately be determined entirely in the political field: whether the general election in June and presidential election later next year will take place peacefully. And, more importantly, whether the election outcomes will be gracefully accepted by the losing and winning parties, to allow for a smooth transition to a new government with credibility and legitimacy. \par \par \uc2  What all this implies is that no new private investment, either domestic or foreign, will likely be made until 2000, while \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector investment is out of the question as the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  will continually be preoccupied with \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social safety net programs, food security, the costs of bank restructuring and other operating costs. Virtually all foreign capital flows will be foreign-aid funds to fill the big state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  hole and finance various restructuring programs. \par \par \uc2  But not all things in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  look so gloomy. Barring a new bout of massive violence and political conflicts, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook next year should be much better than this year, when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to contract by between 13.5 percent and 15 percent, meaning a decline of about 20 percent from last year's growth of about 5 percent. \par \par \uc2  The most promising businesses remain those based on local resources, such as food crops and other agrobusinesses (fisheries and tree crops) and mining, barring any security disruptions by people who have been increasingly demanding a fairer share of the wealth extracted from their areas. \par \par \uc2  Official estimates put next year's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  at a plus or negative growth of 1 percent, though private analysts are more pessimistic, foreseeing a contraction of up to 5 percent. This means \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  suffering will prevail, though with much lesser pains. Not many new jobs will be generated but no new massive layoffs will occur either. \par \par \uc2  Similar to the situation this year, most developments in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  field remain contingent on the rupiah's exchange rate. Fortunately, the rupiah has been stabilizing at around Rp 7,500 to the dollar in recent weeks, compared to as high as Rp 15,000 last June. Though the appreciation has been attributed partly to government intervention into a very thin market, currency stability at the current level is a key to checking inflation at the target range of 15 percent to 20 percent, as against 76 percent this year. Controlled inflation is, in turn, crucial for further lowering bank \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  from their current level of more than 40 percent. \par \par \uc2  Provided the bank recapitalization program runs according to the prescribed schedule, lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will reopen the credit taps which have virtually been closed since early this year. Lower costs of capital will enable more export-oriented enterprises to raise production rates, and the ones currently hamstrung by the punitive costs of funds to resume production. However, industries that depend entirely on the domestic market will remain on a tightrope due to the depressed purchasing power of most consumers. \par \par \uc2  The capital market will get a slight boon from declining \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , though trading activities will remain weak and limited to the bluest blue chip companies in the virtual absence of foreign investors. This sector will still not be able to resume its function as an alternative source of capital to fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  operations. Foreign credit lines will also remain frozen until the restructuring of the huge corporate foreign debt overhang. \par \par \uc2  So, all in all, not much will really happen in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  field next year as new investment decisions will be put on hold until a new government is in place. The top priority for those still in operations is to survive. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924ducn002ll\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
