\par\par \b \uc2  Labor condition likely to worsen in 1999 - Observers. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Ridwan Max Sijabat \par \uc2 764 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 December 1998\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  2 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1998 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): Observers predicted on Monday that labor conditions would worsen next year due to the prolonged \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political crises, warning that an unemployment rate of 38 million out of the total work force of 90 million represented a ticking time bomb. \par \par \uc2  Datuk Bagindo of the Federation of All Indonesian Workers Union and \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  legislator Ismoe Handoko shared the dire outlook, with Ismoe raising alarms over possible "disintegration and social revolution". \par \par \uc2  But Minister of Manpower Fahmi Idris was optimistic that the high unemployment rate could be mitigated by increasing the export of labor. \par \par \uc2  Speaking separately, Fahmi said the government would fight to reduce the unemployment rate to "between 10 and 15 million from the current 20 million." \par \par \uc2  Datuk insisted that around 38 million Indonesians will have lost their jobs by the end of the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year in March because of continued dismissals by troubled companies. Included in this figure were 5 million new graduates and school dropouts who could not find jobs. \par \par \uc2  "We are very pessimistic about labor conditions next year because of the poor \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition this year and the political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the coming months before the general election in June," he said. \par \par \uc2  He linked the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of minus 15 percent and the inflation rate of 75 percent with the dismissal of 15 million workers over 1998. He did not believe there would be changes in the business climate and labor condition next year. \par \par \uc2  "If the government is honest, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year is far below minus 15 percent and the inflation rate has reached 400 percent," he said, adding that more than 50 percent, or 110 million, Indonesians are now living in poverty. \par \par \uc2  High unemployment rates combined with political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  are a time bomb that could explode in the near future, he said. \par \par \uc2  "Violence, looting, robberies and other crimes will be prevalent in all parts of the country, especially in densely-populated Java," he said. \par \par \uc2  Ismoe also expressed concern over the political situation. \par \par \uc2  "More and more people can no longer eat three times a day because they lost their jobs, while those in the political elite are busy taking care of their own interests, and there are no signs the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis will abate in the coming months," he said. \par \par \uc2  "Under these negative changes in society, crimes, looting, violence and rioting linked to religious and ethnic group affiliations will likely be rampant. It is probable that the reform movement will turn into a social revolution," he said. \par \par \uc2  Optimism \par \par \uc2  Fahmi expressed his optimism that the labor situation would improve in the coming year because of some expected \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  improvements. \par \par \uc2  "Despite poor \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, the government is optimistic that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow from the current minus 15 percent to minus 5 percent in the coming year and the inflation rate will be maintained at a rate of less than 20 percent," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said the government is determined to reduce the unemployment rate to between 10 million and 15 million from the current 20 million. \par \par \uc2  Besides "expanding job opportunities at home", the government would encourage the export of labor to ease the unemployment problem. \par \par \uc2  "The labor export program will continue, although it is not now a strategic way to solve the unemployment problem," he said. \par \par \uc2  Ismoe concurred on this matter, and said Indonesia should accelerate its efforts to promote cooperation with other countries, especially those in the Middle East, so they would be willing to open their markets to Indonesian workers. \par \par \uc2  "Many countries have opened their labor markets to Indonesian workers but the government has been slow in its response," he said. \par \par \uc2  He said that he recently visited Kuwait, Qatar, United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia, and found the countries eager to employ more semi-skilled and skilled workers from Indonesia. \par \par \uc2  He added that the Ministry of Foreign Affairs should also help by using its diplomatic relations to seek more job opportunities for dismissed Indonesian workers. \par \par \uc2  Both Ismoe and Datuk urged the government to carry out the social safety net program to employ as many dismissed workers as possible. \par \par \uc2  "Workers need no rulings, ILO (International Labor Organization) Conventions or advice from the government. They need jobs and money to survive the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardships," Ismoe said. \par \par \uc2  Datuk hailed the government's plan to provide Rp 17 trillion to finance labor-intensive projects to help jobless people in the coming year. \par \par \uc2  "We want the social aid to trickle down to all those who are waiting for it," he said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1998 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010924duct0028h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
