\par\par \b \uc2  1999, a perilous year for the local bourse. \b0\par\par\uc2  By Aloysius Unditu \par \uc2 1,212 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 January 1999\par \uc2 Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par  9 \par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 1999 The Jakarta Post\par \par \uc2  JAKARTA (JP): The country's financial market has gone through its worst doldrums year in decades with both the rupiah and local stock prices losing much of their value. \par \par \uc2  Nevertheless, both the rupiah and stock prices have rebounded to some extent, shaking off some of the worst damage. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah bounced back to 8,000 against the U.S. dollar from a historic low of 17,000 in January, 1998 and 15,250 in July, 1998. But it is still 68 percent lower than its pre-crisis level of 2,450. \par \par \uc2  The Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) Composite Index, the main gauge of local stock performance, now rests slightly over 400 points, up from its worst standing in five years of 251.83 points recorded in September. \par \par \uc2  Looking ahead, analysts still paint vague pictures for 1999, with investor confidence remaining low due to various social and political \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  looming in 1999. \par \par \uc2  On the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fronts, all indicators say that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crisis will not end fairly soon. Growth will remain negative in 1999, inflation and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  will stay fairly high and domestic demand weak. \par \par \uc2  And predicting the level of the rupiah should prove to be a tricky issue. But most analysts agree that the rupiah would stay at the current level at least until March, the end of the 1998/1999 \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year, until such time as multibillion dollars worth of official offshore funds flow in. \par \par \uc2  After March, the fate of the rupiah will remain \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the government has yet to get any commitment from any offshore donors to finance the 1999/2000 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  The level of the rupiah would determine the fate of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and that of corporations, especially those with significant offshore debts. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah's sharp depreciation against the American dollar has badly affected earnings of the country's listed firms. The foreign exchange loss serves as the primary source of the problem for most debt-ridden companies. \par \par \uc2  The sudden fall in the rupiah in earlier 1998 had caused local companies with unhedged offshore debts to join in a massive dollar-buying spree, which consequently forced the rupiah to sink even further against the dollar. \par \par \uc2  In response to such frantic dollar-buying, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , raised benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for one-month promissory notes (SBI) to 40 percent in March and eventually to 70 percent in late August to arrest the currency's fall. \par \par \uc2  As the benchmark rose, deposit rates at commercial banks soared even higher. \par \par \uc2  Vicious circle \par \par \uc2  Following the rates increase, the vicious circle began. Companies could not service their debts, and thus, non-performing loans soared; banks would not lend money as most corporations could not afford it. Then, banks went bust. \par \par \uc2  Most corporations themselves technically went bankrupt as their foreign debt ballooned in terms of rupiah due to the depreciation of the currency. \par \par \uc2  The fundamentals of most listed firms were no longer a meaningful guide for most investors as almost 90 percent of the total 289 listed firms in the local bourse were on the brink of bankruptcy. \par \par \uc2  Stocks of resource-based companies in mining and telecommunications could be excluded as their performance remained good due to their dollar-denominated earnings. \par \par \uc2  Yet, in a high interest rate situation, investing in stocks was not a choice for most investors. They would rather put their money in a risk-free, fixed-income instrument like the SBIs which also offer higher yields. \par \par \uc2  As a result of that, most share prices in the local market declined further. Many of them were traded under their par value, with some of them valued at Rp 50 per share, a price which was cheaper than a single clove cigarette. \par \par \uc2  Worse still, most foreign fund managers continued to discard all their portfolio investment here and fled the country following the bloody May riots which eventually forced the authoritarian former president Soeharto to resign and hand over the presidency to then Vice President B.J. Habibie. \par \par \uc2  Even under Habibie's administration, foreign investors remained concerned over his ability to introduce clear-cut political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reform agenda in bringing the country out of its worst crisis in decades. \par \par \uc2  Habibie's new administration has since been rocked by a persistent wave of antigovernment protests. \par \par \uc2  Despite this being so, the financial market has improved in the last three months. \par \par \uc2  The rupiah has stabilized at around 8,000 against the dollar since October, shrugging off various outbreaks of political and social unrest which occurred during the period. \par \par \uc2  A chief economist at Danareksa Sekuritas, Rino Agung Effendi, however, warned that the rupiah's stability could be unsustainable as it was gained through intervention. \par \par \uc2  Although the government has repeatedly denied that it intervened in the market recently, its movement of dollar offshore loans into rupiah in the currency market to finance its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  had just the same effects as intervention. \par \par \uc2  Similarly trading volume and transaction value in the Jakarta Stock Exchange (JSX) have been improving during the past three months. \par \par \uc2  Despite the deepening crisis, total trading volume in the local stock market rose 18.9 percent to 91 billion shares changing hands in 1998 compared to 77 billion shares in 1997. \par \par \uc2  Total transaction value, however, declined 16.67 percent to Rp 100 trillion against Rp 120 trillion. \par \par \uc2  Average daily trading volume rose 17.8 percent to 367 million shares traded last year, compared to 311 million shares in 1997. But daily transaction value slid 17.3 percent to Rp 404 billion from Rp 489 billion. \par \par \uc2  The amount of total funds raised through the local hammered bourse declined by 47.9 percent to Rp 10.2 trillion as of Dec. 23, 1998 against Rp 19.6 trillion in 1997. \par \par \uc2  Meanwhile, total market capitalization rose 9.9 percent to Rp 176 trillion in 1998 compared to Rp 160 trillion in the previous year. \par \par \uc2  "That shows that our market is not that badly affected by the crisis," JSX president Cyrill D. Noerhadi said. \par \par \uc2  Financial analysts said that the recovery of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial market will significantly depend on three factors: the rupiah's fate, the recovery of investor confidence and political stability. \par \par \uc2  Stock market analyst Hasan Zein Mahmud, also a former JSX president, said political stability at home would remain the key factor in assessing the prospects of the country's financial market next year. \par \par \uc2  He said failure on the part of President B.J. Habibie's administration to put on the general election both on time and peacefully would only perpetuate the current crisis. \par \par \uc2  "A successful and fair general election will encourage investors to consider investing in Indonesia, but if the process fails, everybody will still be in the dark," Hasan said. \par \par \uc2  The Indonesian government is scheduled to hold a general election on June 7 in 1999 to elect members of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \par \par \uc2  Following the election, the People's Consultative Assembly, the country's highest \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  body whose members include House members and appointees, would convene to elect a new president and vice president. \par \par \uc2  "If the two political agendas proceed peacefully, we can expect foreign investors to return. Otherwise we do not know where we are heading," a research director at BNI Securities, Adrian Rusmana, said. \par \par \uc2  Copyright 1999 The Jakarta Post. \par \par \uc2 Document jkpost0020010906dv12001g4\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
